fields.body:
The Institute for the Promotion of Mediaeval Medicine works to reverse the advancements of post-15th Century science, and to restore the theories and practices of mediaeval medicine to the status they enjoyed in the Dark Ages.

The Institute is a major research and teaching centre.

News & Events plugins

This page features two News & Events plugins.

News and events items are added to the database; a News & Events plugin in a page will publish the appropriate ones for that page and at the particular moment the page is loaded.

One, on the right, is configured to publish the top three events in a vertical format, together with their summaries and metadata.

The other, below, publishes the top three news articles, in horizontal format.

Please contact

This person has the "Please contact" field set up so that a colleague's contact details will be published instead of his own.

This is useful when a Person is away on leave, or perhaps is simply lucky enough to have a secretary who will take calls for them (as this one is).

Roles

The Professor, as well as his roles in the Institute, is also a member of other important organisations in the field, as you can see under Roles & memberships.

Events

Professor Brooks is also a featured speaker at the 2011 Dark Ages Society Conference, as you can see in Events.

Contrary to the claims of modern science, more and more evidence is accumulating to demonstrate that malaria, far from being a virus transmitted in the saliva of the mosquito, is actually caused by bad air.

Researchers at the Bad Air Research Centre, led by , have recently completed widely-acclaimed research across the undrained swamps of coastal southern Italy.

The links in the paragraph on the left have been added using the Links plugin. Arkestra is intelligent enough to know how to punctuate an inline list of items correctly: by separating items with commas, no comma after the second last item, and inserting and between the last two items (and is the default, but can be overridden if required - for example, sometimes or might be appropriate).

Vacancies and Studentships are very similar.

Each belongs to a particular Entity - the organisation or part of the organisation that will be responsible for it - but can also be sent to be published at the pages of other entities if required.

This one belongs to (is hosted by) the Centre for Research into Mediaeval Dentistry, but will also appear elsewhere - in Publish to, the Institute of Mediaeval Medicine has also been chosen.

Like News and Events items, Vacancies and Studentships have date (a Closing date for applications) and other metadata.

Again, just like most Arkestra objects, they can be external - if a vacancy appears on some other website, it's very easy to add them to Arkestra if they are of interest.

InsertionPoints

This footer, three columns wide, is defined as an InsertionPoint. It allows content to be defined, using a freestanding Placeholder and all the plugins you allow for it, and then delivered into templates.

This footer will appear throughout the site, except where a template overrides it (which perhaps could use its own InsertionPoint).

How to use

  1. in your template(s), place a {% insert "<insertion_point>" %} (if there wasn't one already, this will create a new InsertionPoint object in the database)
  2. add the content to the InsertionPoint in the admin as required
  3. there's no step 3
The showered him with petals and gifts

About this footer

This footer, and everything in it (including the dynamic content in the final column) is provided by an Insert.

Using Inserts

  1. in your template(s), use {% insert "my_insertion_point" %} -this templatetag will then get_or_create() the appropriate Insert object in the database
  2. find the Insert in the admin, and adds plug-based content to its Placeholder.
  3. there is no step three

Default settings

Titles only, date order

Horizontal

The News & Events plugin provides a convenient way to place lists of current news and events items into other content.

The way these lists are displayed is configured in the plugin. This site's contains two examples; some others are show below.

The default

News & events, side-by-side, listed vertically, showing details, ordered by importance as well as date, and showing date groups:

A horizontal list

Simpler lists

Three items each, titles only:

A stacked view

The lists can be stacked as well as placed side-by-side:

Arkestra makes intelligent use of images.

Arkestra can associate images with other objects, displaying them automatically as required, resizing them for different purposes.

Using Arkestra will scale and crop images automatically, preserving important detail.

Images can also be inserted manually into content using a flexible and sophisticated plugin which also calculates appropriate sizes.

Arkestra uses image metadata to work out which parts of the image are most significant.

In these examples, Shane MacGowan's blessed teeth have been set as the focus of the image.

How neatly all these lines line up, thanks to the magic of Arkestra!
